	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Glop Top Question</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />What are under these glop top's on like mario NES boards?  Can they be easily removed?

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>lidnariq</b> [ Sat Feb 14, 2015 11:22 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Glop Top Question</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />A bare silicon die. Wire bonding from the PCB to that die. Not much else.<br /><br />In NES cartridges, the epoxy blobs are usually ROMs, with the same wire bond order as the legs would have had.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>tokumaru</b> [ Mon Feb 16, 2015 6:09 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Glop Top Question</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />The same thing you'd find inside a regular DIP chip, but without any packaging. You cant remove the black stuff without destroying what's under it, AFAIK.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

